
[1]shoulder

   SHOULDER, n.

   1. The joint by which the arm of a human being or the fore leg of a
   quadruped is connected with the body; or in man, the projection formed
   by the bones called scapula or shoulder blades, which extend from the
   basis of the neck in a horizontal direction.

   2. The upper joint of the fore leg of an animal cut for th emarket; as
   a shoulder of mutton.

   3. Shoulders, in the plural, the upper part of the back.

   Adown her shoulders fell her length of hair. Dryden.

   4. Figuratively, support; sustaining power; or that which elevates and
   sustains.

   For on thy shoulders do I build my seat. Shak.

   5. Among artificers, something like the human shoulder; a horizontal or
   rectangular projection from the body of a thing.

   SHOULDER, v.t.

   1. To push or thrust with the shoulder; to push with violence.

   Around her numberless the rabble flow'd,
